   
   (Message)
   
   
   
   The program crashes when run with a command line argument of extremely long
   length (over 1000 A's). After inspecting the program state with the `debug`
   tool, we see that the program is in a state of aborting due to a segmentation
   fault, but the `info locals` command shows that no local variables are
   defined. The `bt` command shows a stack trace consisting only of system
   frames, indicating that the program ran to completion but produced incorrect
   output that the test caught.
   
   Looking at the source code surrounding line 13 of `program.c` with the
   `get_code_surrounding` tool, we see:
   
   ```c
   void function(long long arr[]) {
       arr[13] = arr[12] + arr[11];
       arr[14] = arr[13] + arr[15];
       //...
   }
   ```
   
   The program appears to be a simple arithmetic function that takes an array of
   long long integers as input. However, the extremely long command line
   argument provided to the program likely causes a buffer overflow when the
   function attempts to access the array.
   
   The root cause of the crash is a buffer overflow when accessing the `arr`
   array. When the program is run with a command line argument of extremely long
   length, the `arr` array is not initialized properly, leading to undefined
   behavior when the function attempts to access its elements.
   
   ROOT CAUSE: `program.c:13: accessing uninitilized array element`
   
   LOCAL FIX:
   
   ```c
   void function(long long arr[]) {
       if (arr == NULL) {
           arr = malloc(16 * sizeof(long long));
       }
       arr[13] = arr[12] + arr[11];
       arr[14] = arr[13] + arr[15];
       //...
   }
   ```
   
   However, this fix is still incomplete as it does not address the underlying
   issue of the buffer overflow.
   
   GLOBAL FIX:
   
   ```c
   void function(long long arr[], long long arr_size) {
       if (arr == NULL) {
           arr = malloc(arr_size * sizeof(long long));
       }
       if (arr_size < 16) {
           printf("Error: Insufficient array size\n");
           return;
       }
       arr[13] = arr[12] + arr[11];
       arr[14] = arr[13] + arr[15];
       //...
   }
   ```
   
   In this revised version, we added a `long long arr_size` parameter to the
   function to specify the size of the array. We also added a check to ensure
   that the array size is sufficient before attempting to access its elements.
   This prevents the buffer overflow and provides a more robust solution.
